# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thermogravimetric-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is most commonly used in the treatment of organic materials.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] It is one of the processes involved in the charring of wood.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In general, pyrolysis of organic substances produces volatile products and leaves char, a carbon-rich solid residue.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Extreme pyrolysis, which leaves mostly carbon as the residue, is called carbonization.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is considered one of the steps in the processes of gasification or combustion.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Compared to syngas, pyrolysis gas has a high percentage of heavy tar fractions, which condense at relatively high temperatures, preventing its direct use in gas burners and internal combustion engines.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The process is used heavily in the chemical industry, for example, to produce ethylene, many forms of carbon, and other chemicals from petroleum, coal, and even wood, or to produce coke from coal.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] It is used also in the conversion of natural gas (primarily methane) into hydrogen gas and solid carbon char, recently introduced on an industrial scale.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Aspirational applications of pyrolysis would convert biomass into syngas and biochar, waste plastics back into usable oil, or waste into safely disposable substances.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is one of the various types of chemical degradation processes that occur at higher temperatures (above the boiling point of water or other solvents).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] It differs from other processes like combustion and hydrolysis in that it usually does not involve the addition of other reagents such as oxygen (O 2, in combustion) or water (in hydrolysis).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis produces solids (char), condensable liquids (heavy and light oils, and tar), and non-condensable gasses.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is different from gasification.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In the chemical process industry, pyrolysis refers to a partial thermal degradation of carbonaceous materials that takes place in an inert (oxygen free) atmosphere and produces both gases, liquids and solids.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The pyrolysis can be extended to full gasification that produces mainly gaseous output, often with the addition of e.g. water steam to gasify residual carbonic solids, see Steam reforming.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Other pyrolysis types come from a different classification that focuses on the pyrolysis operating conditions and heating system used, which have an impact on the yield of the pyrolysis products.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis has been used for turning wood into charcoal since ancient times.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The ancient Egyptians used the liquid fraction obtained from the pyrolysis of cedar wood in their embalming process.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The dry distillation of wood remained the major source of methanol into the early 20th century.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis was instrumental in the discovery of many chemical substances, such as phosphorus from ammonium sodium hydrogen phosphate NH4NaHPO4 in concentrated urine, oxygen from mercuric oxide, and various nitrates.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis generally consists of heating the material above its decomposition temperature, breaking chemical bonds in its molecules.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The fragments usually become smaller molecules, but may combine to produce residues with larger molecular mass, even amorphous covalent solids.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In many settings, some amounts of oxygen, water, or other substances may be present, so that combustion, hydrolysis, or other chemical processes may occur besides pyrolysis proper.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Sometimes those chemicals are added intentionally, as in the burning of firewood, in the traditional manufacture of charcoal, and in the steam cracking of crude oil.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Conversely, the starting material may be heated in a vacuum or in an inert atmosphere to avoid chemical side reactions (such as combustion or hydrolysis).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis in a vacuum also lowers the boiling point of the byproducts, improving their recovery.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Because pyrolysis takes place at high temperatures which exceed the autoignition temperature of the produced gases, an explosion risk exists if oxygen is present.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Careful temperature control is needed for pyrolysis systems, which can be accomplished with pyrolysis controller.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis also produces various toxic gases, such as carbon monoxide.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The greatest risk of fire, explosion, and release of toxic gases comes when the system is starting up and shutting down, operating intermittently, or during operational upsets.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Inert gas purging is essential to manage inherent explosion risks.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The procedure is not trivial and failure to keep oxygen out has led to accidents.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Conversion of CBD to THC can be brought about by pyrolysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] This pizza is pyrolyzed, almost completely carbonized.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis has many applications in food preparation.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Caramelization is the pyrolysis of sugars in food (often after the sugars have been produced by the breakdown of polysaccharides).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The distinctive flavors are used in many dishes; for instance, caramelized onion is used in French onion soup.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The temperatures needed for caramelization lie above the boiling point of water.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Frying oil can easily rise above the boiling point.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Putting a lid on the frying pan keeps the water in, re-condensing some and keeping the temperature too cool to brown.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis of food can also be undesirable, as in the charring of burnt food (at temperatures too low for the oxidative combustion of carbon to produce flames and burn the food to ash).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Carbon and carbon-rich materials have desirable properties but are nonvolatile, even at high temperatures.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Consequently, pyrolysis is used to produce many kinds of carbon; these can be used for fuel, as reagents in steelmaking (coke), and as structural materials.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Charcoal is a less smoky fuel than pyrolyzed wood.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Some cities ban, or used to ban, wood fires; when residents only use charcoal (and similarly treated rock coal, called *coke*) air pollution is significantly reduced.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In cities where people do not generally cook or heat with fires, this is not needed.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In the mid-20th century, "smokeless" legislation in Europe required cleaner-burning techniques, such as coke fuel and smoke-burning incinerators as an effective measure to reduce air pollution.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The amount of volatiles varies with the source material, but is typically 25–30% of it by weight.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] High temperature pyrolysis is used on an industrial scale to convert coal into coke.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] This is useful in metallurgy, where the higher temperatures are necessary for many processes, such as steelmaking.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Volatile by-products of this process are also often useful, including benzene and pyridine.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Coke can also be produced from the solid residue left from petroleum refining.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The original vascular structure of the wood and the pores created by escaping gases combine to produce a light and porous material.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] By starting with a dense wood-like material, such as nutshells or peach stones, one obtains a form of charcoal with particularly fine pores (and hence a much larger pore surface area), called activated carbon, which is used as an adsorbent for a wide range of chemical substances.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Biochar is the residue of incomplete organic pyrolysis, e.g., from cooking fires.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] It is a key component of the terra preta soils associated with ancient indigenous communities of the Amazon basin.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Terra preta is much sought by local farmers for its superior fertility and capacity to promote and retain an enhanced suite of beneficial microbiota, compared to the typical red soil of the region.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Efforts are underway to recreate these soils through biochar, the solid residue of pyrolysis of various materials, mostly organic waste.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Carbon fibers are filaments of carbon that can be used to make very strong yarns and textiles.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Carbon fiber items are often produced by spinning and weaving the desired item from fibers of a suitable polymer, and then pyrolyzing the material at a high temperature (from 1,500–3,000 °C or 2,730–5,430 °F).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The first carbon fibers were made from rayon, but polyacrylonitrile has become the most common starting material.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] For their first workable electric lamps, Joseph Wilson Swan and Thomas Edison used carbon filaments made by pyrolysis of cotton yarns and bamboo splinters, respectively.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is the reaction used to coat a preformed substrate with a layer of pyrolytic carbon.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] This is typically done in a fluidized bed reactor heated to 1,000–2,000 °C or 1,830–3,630 °F.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolytic carbon coatings are used in many applications, including artificial heart valves.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is the basis of several methods for producing fuel from biomass, i.e. lignocellulosic biomass.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Crops studied as biomass feedstock for pyrolysis include native North American prairie grasses such as *switchgrass* and bred versions of other grasses such as *Miscantheus giganteus*.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Other sources of organic matter as feedstock for pyrolysis include greenwaste, sawdust, waste wood, leaves, vegetables, nut shells, straw, cotton trash, rice hulls, and orange peels.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Animal waste including poultry litter, dairy manure, and potentially other manures are also under evaluation.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Some industrial byproducts are also suitable feedstock including paper sludge, distillers grain, and sewage sludge.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In the biomass components, the pyrolysis of hemicellulose happens between 210 and 310 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The pyrolysis of cellulose starts from 300 to 315 °C and ends at 360–380 °C, with a peak at 342–354 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Lignin starts to decompose at about 200 °C and continues until 1000 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Synthetic diesel fuel by pyrolysis of organic materials is not yet economically competitive.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Higher efficiency is sometimes achieved by **flash pyrolysis**, in which finely divided feedstock is quickly heated to between 350 and 500 °C (660 and 930 °F) for less than two seconds.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Syngas is usually produced by pyrolysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The low quality of oils produced through pyrolysis can be improved by physical and chemical processes, which might drive up production costs, but may make sense economically as circumstances change.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] There is also the possibility of integrating with other processes such as mechanical biological treatment and anaerobic digestion.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Fast pyrolysis is also investigated for biomass conversion.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Fuel bio-oil can also be produced by hydrous pyrolysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Methane pyrolysis is an industrial process for "turquoise" hydrogen production from methane by removing solid carbon from natural gas.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] This one-step process produces hydrogen in high volume at low cost (less than steam reforming with carbon sequestration).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] No deep well injection of carbon dioxide is needed.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Only water is released when hydrogen is used as the fuel for fuel-cell electric heavy truck transportation, gas turbine electric power generation, and hydrogen for industrial processes including producing ammonia fertilizer and cement.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Methane pyrolysis is the process operating around 1065 °C for producing hydrogen from natural gas that allows removal of carbon easily (solid carbon is a byproduct of the process).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The industrial quality solid carbon can then be sold or landfilled and is not released into the atmosphere, avoiding emission of greenhouse gas (GHG) or ground water pollution from a landfill.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In 2015, a company called Monolith Materials built a pilot plant in Redwood City, CA to study scaling Methane Pyrolysis using renewable power in the process.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] A successful pilot project then led to a larger commercial-scale demonstration plant in Hallam, Nebraska in 2016.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] As of 2020, this plant is operational and can produce around 14 metric tons of hydrogen per day.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In 2021, the US Department of Energy backed Monolith Materials' plans for major expansion with a $1B loan guarantee.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The funding will help produce a plant capable of generating 164 metric tons of hydrogen per day by 2024.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pilots with gas utilities and biogas plants are underway with companies like Modern Hydrogen.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Volume production is also being evaluated in the BASF "methane pyrolysis at scale" pilot plant, the chemical engineering team at University of California - Santa Barbara and in such research laboratories as Karlsruhe Liquid-metal Laboratory (KALLA).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Power for process heat consumed is only one-seventh of the power consumed in the water electrolysis method for producing hydrogen.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The Australian company Hazer Group was founded in 2010 to commercialise technology originally developed at the University of Western Australia.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The company was listed on the ASX in December 2015.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] It is completing a commercial demonstration project to produce renewable hydrogen and graphite from wastewater and iron ore as a process catalyst use technology created by the University of Western Australia (UWA).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The Commercial Demonstration Plant project is an Australian first, and expected to produce around 100 tonnes of fuel-grade hydrogen and 380 tonnes of graphite each year starting in 2023.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] "10 December 2021: Hazer Group (ASX: HZR) regret to advise that there has been a delay to the completion of the fabrication of the reactor for the Hazer Commercial Demonstration Project (CDP).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The American company C-Zero's technology converts natural gas into hydrogen and solid carbon.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The hydrogen provides clean, low-cost energy on demand, while the carbon can be permanently sequestered.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] C-Zero announced in June 2022 that it closed a $34 million financing round led by SK Gas, a subsidiary of South Korea's second-largest conglomerate, the SK Group.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] SK Gas was joined by two other new investors, Engie New Ventures and Trafigura, one of the world's largest physical commodities trading companies, in addition to participation from existing investors including Breakthrough Energy Ventures, Eni Next, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, and AP Ventures.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Funding was for C-Zero's first pilot plant, which was expected to be online in Q1 2023.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The plant may be capable of producing up to 400 kg of hydrogen per day from natural gas with no CO2 emissions.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] One of the world's largest chemical companies, BASF, has been researching hydrogen pyrolysis for more than 10 years.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is used to produce ethylene, the chemical compound produced on the largest scale industrially (>110 million tons/year in 2005).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In this process, hydrocarbons from petroleum are heated to around 600 °C (1,112 °F) in the presence of steam; this is called steam cracking.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The resulting ethylene is used to make antifreeze (ethylene glycol), PVC (via vinyl chloride), and many other polymers, such as polyethylene and polystyrene.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The process of metalorganic vapour-phase epitaxy (MOCVD) entails pyrolysis of volatile organometallic compounds to give semiconductors, hard coatings, and other applicable materials.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The reactions entail thermal degradation of precursors, with deposition of the inorganic component and release of the hydrocarbons as gaseous waste.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Since it is an atom-by-atom deposition, these atoms organize themselves into crystals to form the bulk semiconductor.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Gallium arsenide, another semiconductor, forms upon co-pyrolysis of trimethylgallium and arsine.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis can also be used to treat municipal solid waste and plastic waste.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The main advantage is the reduction in volume of the waste.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In principle, pyrolysis will regenerate the monomers (precursors) to the polymers that are treated, but in practice the process is neither a clean nor an economically competitive source of monomers.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In tire waste management, tire pyrolysis is a well-developed technology.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Other products from car tire pyrolysis include steel wires, carbon black and bitumen.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The area faces legislative, economic, and marketing obstacles.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Oil derived from tire rubber pyrolysis has a high sulfur content, which gives it high potential as a pollutant; consequently it should be desulfurized.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Alkaline pyrolysis of sewage sludge at low temperature of 500 °C can enhance H 2 production with in-situ carbon capture.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The use of NaOH (sodium hydroxide) has the potential to produce H 2-rich gas that can be used for fuels cells directly.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] State of Georgia announced a joint effort with Igneo Technologies to build an $85 million large electronics recycling plant in the Port of Savannah.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The project will focus on lower-value, plastics-heavy devices in the waste stream using multiple shredders and furnaces using pyrolysis technology.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Waste from pyrolysis itself can also be used for useful products.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis has also been used in trying to mitigate tobacco waste.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] One method was done where tobacco waste was separated into two categories, TLW (Tobacco Leaf Waste) and TSW (Tobacco Stick Waste).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] TLW was determined to be any waste from cigarettes and TSW was determined to be any waste from electronic cigarettes.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Both TLW and TSW were dried at 80 °C for 24 hours and stored in a desiccator.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Samples were grounded so that the contents were uniform.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Tobacco Waste (TW) also contains inorganic (metal) contents, which was determined using an inductively coupled plasma-optical spectrometer.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Thermo-gravimetric analysis was used to thermally degrade four samples (TLW, TSW, glycerol, and guar gum) and monitored under specific dynamic temperature conditions.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] About one gram of both TLW and TSW were used in the pyrolysis tests.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] During these analysis tests, CO 2 and N 2 were used as atmospheres inside of a tubular reactor that was built using quartz tubing.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] For both CO 2 and N 2 atmospheres the flow rate was 100 mL min−1.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] External heating was created via a tubular furnace.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The pyrogenic products were classified into three phases.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The first phase was biochar, a solid residue produced by the reactor at 650 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The second phase liquid hydrocarbons were collected by a cold solvent trap and sorted by using chromatography.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The third and final phase was analyzed using an online micro GC unit and those pyrolysates were gases.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Two different types of experiments were conducted: one-stepwise pyrolysis and two-stepwise pyrolysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] One-stepwise pyrolysis consisted of a constant heating rate (10 °C min−1) from 30 to 720 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In the second step of the two-stepwise pyrolysis test the pyrolysates from the one-stepwise pyrolysis were pyrolyzed in the second heating zone which was controlled isothermally at 650 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The two-stepwise pyrolysis was used to focus primarily on how well CO 2 affects carbon redistribution when adding heat through the second heating zone.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] First noted was the thermolytic behaviors of TLW and TSW in both the CO 2 and N 2 environments.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] For both TLW and TSW the thermolytic behaviors were identical at less than or equal to 660 °C in the CO 2 and N 2 environments.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The differences between the environments start to occur when temperatures increase above 660 °C and the residual mass percentages significantly decrease in the CO 2 environment compared to that in the N 2 environment.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] This observation is likely due to the Boudouard reaction, where we see spontaneous gasification happening when temperatures exceed 710 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Although these observations were seen at temperatures lower than 710 °C it is most likely due to the catalytic capabilities of inorganics in TLW.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] It was further investigated by doing ICP-OES measurements and found that a fifth of the residual mass percentage was Ca species.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] CaCO 3 is used in cigarette papers and filter material, leading to the explanation that degradation of CaCO 3 causes pure CO 2 reacting with CaO in a dynamic equilibrium state.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] This being the reason for seeing mass decay between 660 °C and 710 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Differences in differential thermogram (DTG) peaks for TLW were compared to TSW.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] TLW had four distinctive peaks at 87, 195, 265, and 306 °C whereas TSW had two major drop offs at 200 and 306 °C with one spike in between.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The four peaks indicated that TLW contains more diverse types of additives than TSW.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The residual mass percentage between TLW and TSW was further compared, where the residual mass in TSW was less than that of TLW for both CO 2 and N 2 environments concluding that TSW has higher quantities of additives than TLW.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The one-stepwise pyrolysis experiment showed different results for the CO 2 and N 2 environments.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] During this process the evolution of 5 different notable gases were observed.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Hydrogen, Methane, Ethane, Carbon Dioxide, and Ethylene all are produced when the thermolytic rate of TLW began to be retarded at greater than or equal to 500 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Thermolytic rate begins at the same temperatures for both the CO 2 and N 2 environment but there is higher concentration of the production of Hydrogen, Ethane, Ethylene, and Methane in the N 2 environment than that in the CO 2 environment.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The concentration of CO in the CO 2 environment is significantly greater as temperatures increase past 600 °C and this is due to CO 2 being liberated from CaCO 3 in TLW.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] This significant increase in CO concentration is why there is lower concentrations of other gases produced in the CO 2 environment due to a dilution effect.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Since pyrolysis is the re-distribution of carbons in carbon substrates into three pyrogenic products.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The CO 2 environment is going to be more effective because the CO 2 reduction into CO allows for the oxidation of pyrolysates to form CO.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In conclusion the CO 2 environment allows a higher yield of gases than oil and biochar.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] When the same process is done for TSW the trends are almost identical therefore the same explanations can be applied to the pyrolysis of TSW.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Harmful chemicals were reduced in the CO 2 environment due to CO formation causing tar to be reduced.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] One-stepwise pyrolysis was not that effective on activating CO 2 on carbon rearrangement due to the high quantities of liquid pyrolysates (tar).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Two-stepwise pyrolysis for the CO 2 environment allowed for greater concentrations of gases due to the second heating zone.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The second heating zone was at a consistent temperature of 650 °C isothermally.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] More reactions between CO 2 and gaseous pyrolysates with longer residence time meant that CO 2 could further convert pyrolysates into CO.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The results showed that the two-stepwise pyrolysis was an effective way to decrease tar content and increase gas concentration by about 10 wt.% for both TLW (64.20 wt.%) and TSW (73.71%).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is also used for *thermal cleaning*, an industrial application to remove organic substances such as polymers, plastics and coatings from parts, products or production components like extruder screws, spinnerets and static mixers.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] During the thermal cleaning process, at temperatures from 310 to 540 °C (600 to 1,000 °F), organic material is converted by pyrolysis and oxidation into volatile organic compounds, hydrocarbons and carbonized gas.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis is used in the production of chemical compounds, mainly, but not only, in the research laboratory.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The area of boron-hydride clusters started with the study of the pyrolysis of diborane (B 2H 6) at ca.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Products include the clusters pentaborane and decaborane.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] These pyrolyses involve not only cracking (to give H 2), but also recondensation.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The synthesis of nanoparticles, zirconia and oxides utilizing an ultrasonic nozzle in a process called ultrasonic spray pyrolysis (USP).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) can be generated from the pyrolysis of different solid waste fractions, such as hemicellulose, cellulose, lignin, pectin, starch, polyethylene (PE), polystyrene (PS), polyvinyl chloride (PVC), and polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] PS, PVC, and lignin generate significant amount of PAHs.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Naphthalene is the most abundant PAH among all the polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] When the temperature is increased from 500 to 900 °C, most PAHs increase.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] With increasing temperature, the percentage of light PAHs decreases and the percentage of heavy PAHs increases.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) is one of the most common techniques to investigate pyrolysis with no limitations of heat and mass transfer.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] The results can be used to determine mass loss kinetics.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Activation energies can be calculated using the Kissinger method or peak analysis-least square method (PA-LSM).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] TGA can couple with Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) and mass spectrometry.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] As the temperature increases, the volatiles generated from pyrolysis can be measured.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In TGA, the sample is loaded first before the increase of temperature, and the heating rate is low (less than 100 °C min−1).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Macro-TGA can use gram-scale samples to investigate the effects of pyrolysis with mass and heat transfer.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] Pyrolysis mass spectrometry (Py-GC-MS) is an important laboratory procedure to determine the structure of compounds.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/pyrolysis] In recent years, machine learning has attracted significant research interest in predicting yields, optimizing parameters, and monitoring pyrolytic processes.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Simultaneous thermal analysis generally refers to the simultaneous application of thermogravimetry and differential scanning calorimetry to one and the same sample in a single instrument.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] The test conditions are perfectly identical for the thermogravimetric analysis and differential scanning calorimetry signals (same atmosphere, gas flow rate, vapor pressure of the sample, heating rate, thermal contact to the sample crucible and sensor, radiation effect, etc.).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] The information gathered can even be enhanced by coupling the simultaneous thermal analysis instrument to an Evolved Gas Analyzer like Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy or mass spectrometry.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Other, less common, methods measure the sound or light emission from a sample, or the electrical discharge from a dielectric material, or the mechanical relaxation in a stressed specimen.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] The essence of all these techniques is that the sample's response is recorded as a function of temperature (and time).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] It is usual to control the temperature in a predetermined way – either by a continuous increase or decrease in temperature at a constant rate (linear heating/cooling) or by carrying out a series of determinations at different temperatures (stepwise isothermal measurements).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Measurements may be carried out in air or under an inert gas (e.g. nitrogen or helium).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Reducing or reactive atmospheres have also been used and measurements are even carried out with the sample surrounded by water or other liquids.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Inverse gas chromatography is a technique which studies the interaction of gases and vapours with a surface - measurements are often made at different temperatures so that these experiments can be considered to come under the auspices of Thermal Analysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Atomic force microscopy uses a fine stylus to map the topography and mechanical properties of surfaces to high spatial resolution.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] By controlling the temperature of the heated tip and/or the sample a form of spatially resolved thermal analysis can be carried out.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Polymers represent another large area in which thermal analysis finds strong applications.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] An example is oxidation induction time by differential scanning calorimetry which can determine the amount of oxidation stabiliser present in a thermoplastic (usually a polyolefin) polymer material.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Compositional analysis is often made using thermogravimetric analysis, which can separate fillers, polymer resin and other additives.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Thermogravimetric analysis can also give an indication of thermal stability and the effects of additives such as flame retardants.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] (See *J.H.Flynn, L.A.Wall J.Res.Nat.Bur.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Thermal analysis of composite materials, such as carbon fibre composites or glass epoxy composites are often carried out using dynamic mechanical analysis, which can measure the stiffness of materials by determining the modulus and damping (energy absorbing) properties of the material.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Aerospace companies often employ these analysers in routine quality control to ensure that products being manufactured meet the required strength specifications.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Formula 1 racing car manufacturers also have similar requirements.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Differential scanning calorimetry is used to determine the curing properties of the resins used in composite materials, and can also confirm whether a resin can be cured and how much heat is evolved during that process.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Application of predictive kinetics analysis can help to fine-tune manufacturing processes.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Another example is that thermogravimetric analysis can be used to measure the fibre content of composites by heating a sample to remove the resin by application of heat and then determining the mass remaining.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Production of many metals (cast iron, grey iron, ductile iron, compacted graphite iron, 3000 series aluminium alloys, copper alloys, silver, and complex steels) are aided by a production technique also referred to as thermal analysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] A sample of liquid metal is removed from the furnace or ladle and poured into a sample cup with a thermocouple embedded in it.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] The temperature is then monitored, and the phase diagram arrests (liquidus, eutectic, and solidus) are noted.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] From this information chemical composition based on the phase diagram can be calculated, or the crystalline structure of the cast sample can be estimated especially for silicon morphology in hypo-eutectic Al-Si cast alloys.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Strictly speaking these measurements are *cooling curves* and a form of sample controlled thermal analysis whereby the cooling rate of the sample is dependent on the cup material (usually bonded sand) and sample volume which is normally a constant due to the use of standard sized sample cups.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] To detect phase evolution and corresponding characteristic temperatures, cooling curve and its first derivative curve should be considered simultaneously.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Examination of cooling and derivative curves is done by using appropriate data analysis software.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] The process consists of plotting, smoothing and curve fitting as well as identifying the reaction points and characteristic parameters.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] This procedure is known as Computer-Aided Cooling Curve Thermal Analysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Advanced techniques use differential curves to locate endothermic inflection points such as gas holes, and shrinkage, or exothermic phases such as carbides, beta crystals, inter crystalline copper, magnesium silicide, iron phosphide's and other phases as they solidify.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Detection limits seem to be around 0.01% to 0.03% of volume.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] In addition, integration of the area between the zero curve and the first derivative is a measure of the specific heat of that part of the solidification which can lead to rough estimates of the percent volume of a phase.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] (Something has to be either known or assumed about the specific heat of the phase versus the overall specific heat.) In spite of this limitation, this method is better than estimates from two dimensional micro analysis, and a lot faster than chemical dissolution.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Most foods undergo temperature variations during production, transport, storage, preparation, and consumption through processes like pasteurization, sterilization, evaporation, cooking, freezing, and chilling.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] These temperatures changes alter the physical and chemical properties of food components which affects the final product's taste, appearance, texture, and stability.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Temperature variations can promote chemical reactions, such as hydrolysis, oxidation, and reduction, or trigger physical changes like evaporation, melting, crystallization, aggregation, or gelation.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] A better understanding of how temperatures influences food properties allows manufacturers to optimize processing conditions and improve quality.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Therefore, food scientists require reliable analytical techniques to monitor these temperature-dependent changes.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Most analytical methods can be adapted for this purpose, including spectroscopy, scattering, and physical methods but thermal analysis is typically reserved for a specific suite of methods.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] These primarily include thermogravimetry and derivative thermogravimetry (TG/DTG), differential thermal analysis (DTA), differential scanning calorimetry (DSC), and the determination of phase transition temperatures.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Power dissipation is an important issue in present-day PCB design.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Power dissipation will result in temperature difference and pose a thermal problem to a chip.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] In addition to the issue of reliability, excess heat will also negatively affect electrical performance and safety.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] The working temperature of an IC should therefore be kept below the maximum allowable limit of the worst case.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] In general, the temperatures of junction and ambient are 125 °C and 55 °C, respectively.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] The ever-shrinking chip size causes the heat to concentrate within a small area and leads to high power density.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Furthermore, denser transistors gathering in a monolithic chip and higher operating frequency cause a worsening of the power dissipation.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-analysis] Removing the heat effectively becomes the critical issue to be resolved.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] The thermal decomposition temperature is the specific temperature at which a material begins to undergo chemical breakdown into simpler substances when subjected to heat, usually identified experimentally by the initial significant mass loss in a thermogravimetric (TGA) curve.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] This marks the onset of observable chemical decomposition, where chemical bonds cleave solely due to thermal energy.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] Since chemical reactions are essentially always occurring, because molecules assume a probability distribution of energies, there is no distinct temperature value at which decomposition spontaneously occurs.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] Therefore, the onset temperature is often used experimentally; this is the temperature at which a chemical reaction occurs at a measurable rate, and is thus highly dependent on the sensitivity of the corresponding instrument.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] The onset temperature can be calculated using differential scanning calorimetry (DSC), which is also sensitive to the rate of heating.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] A higher rate of heating will often display a higher onset temperature due to further kinetic variables such as reaction order, activation energy, and autocatalytic behaviour.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] A simple substance (like water) may exist in equilibrium with its thermal decomposition products, effectively halting the decomposition.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] The equilibrium fraction of decomposed molecules increases with the temperature.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] Since thermal decomposition is a kinetic process, the observed temperature of its beginning in most instances will be a function of the experimental conditions and sensitivity of the experimental setup.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] For a rigorous depiction of the process, the use of thermokinetic modeling is recommended.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] , which is an industrially important product.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] When metals are near the bottom of the reactivity series, their compounds generally decompose easily at high temperatures.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] This is because stronger bonds form between atoms towards the top of the reactivity series, and strong bonds are difficult to break.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] For example, copper is near the bottom of the reactivity series, and copper sulfate (CuSO4), begins to decompose at about 200 °C (473 K; 392 °F), increasing rapidly at higher temperatures to about 560 °C (833 K; 1,040 °F).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] In contrast potassium is near the top of the reactivity series, and potassium sulfate (K2SO4) does not decompose at its melting point of about 1,069 °C (1,342 K; 1,956 °F), nor even at its boiling point.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] Many scenarios in the real world are affected by thermal degradation.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] One of the things affected is fingerprints.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] When anyone touches something, there is residue left from the fingers.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] If fingers are sweaty, or contain more oils, the residue contains many chemicals.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] De Paoli and her colleagues conducted a study testing thermal degradation on certain components found in fingerprints.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] For heat exposure, the amino acid and urea samples started degradation at 100 °C (373 K; 212 °F) and for lactic acid, the decomposition process started around 50 °C (323 K; 122 °F).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermal-decomposition] These components are necessary for further testing, so in the forensics discipline, decomposition of fingerprints is significant.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) is conducted on an instrument referred to as a thermogravimetric analyzer.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] A thermogravimetric analyzer continuously measures mass while the temperature of a sample is changed over time.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Mass, temperature, and time are considered base measurements in thermogravimetric analysis while many additional measures may be derived from these three base measurements.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] A typical thermogravimetric analyzer consists of a precision balance with a sample pan located inside a furnace with a programmable control temperature.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] The temperature is generally increased at constant rate (or for some applications the temperature is controlled for a constant mass loss) to incur a thermal reaction.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] The thermogravimetric data collected from a thermal reaction is compiled into a plot of mass or percentage of initial mass on the y axis versus either temperature or time on the x-axis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] This plot, which is often smoothed, is referred to as a TGA curve.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] The first derivative of the TGA curve (the DTG curve) may be plotted to determine inflection points useful for in-depth interpretations as well as differential thermal analysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] A TGA can be used for materials characterization through analysis of characteristic decomposition patterns.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] It is an especially useful technique for the study of polymeric materials, including thermoplastics, thermosets, elastomers, composites, plastic films, fibers, coatings, paints, and fuels.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] TGA can be used to evaluate the thermal stability of a material.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] In a desired temperature range, if a species is thermally stable, there will be no observed mass change.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Negligible mass loss corresponds to little or no slope in the TGA trace.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] TGA also gives the upper use temperature of a material.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Beyond this temperature the material will begin to degrade.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] TGA is used in the analysis of polymers.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Polymers usually melt before they decompose, thus TGA is mainly used to investigate the thermal stability of polymers.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Most polymers melt or degrade before 200 °C.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] However, there is a class of thermally stable polymers that are able to withstand temperatures of at least 300 °C in air and 500 °C in inert gases without structural changes or strength loss, which can be analyzed by TGA.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] The simplest materials characterization is the residue remaining after a reaction.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] For example, a combustion reaction could be tested by loading a sample into a thermogravimetric analyzer at normal conditions.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] The thermogravimetric analyzer would cause ion combustion in the sample by heating it beyond its ignition temperature.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] The resultant TGA curve plotted with the y-axis as a percentage of initial mass would show the residue at the final point of the curve.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Oxidative mass losses are the most common observable losses in TGA.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Studying the resistance to oxidation in copper alloys is very important.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] For example, NASA (National Aeronautics and Space Administration) is conducting research on advanced copper alloys for their possible use in combustion engines.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] However, oxidative degradation can occur in these alloys as copper oxides form in atmospheres that are rich in oxygen.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Resistance to oxidation is significant because NASA wants to be able to reuse shuttle materials.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] TGA can be used to study the static oxidation of materials such as these for practical use.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Combustion during TG analysis is identifiable by distinct traces made in the TGA thermograms produced.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] One interesting example occurs with samples of as-produced unpurified carbon nanotubes that have a large amount of metal catalyst present.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Due to combustion, a TGA trace can deviate from the normal form of a well-behaved function.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] This phenomenon arises from a rapid temperature change.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] When the weight and temperature are plotted versus time, a dramatic slope change in the first derivative plot is concurrent with the mass loss of the sample and the sudden increase in temperature seen by the thermocouple.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] The mass loss could result from particles of smoke released from burning caused by inconsistencies in the material itself, beyond the oxidation of carbon due to poorly controlled weight loss.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Different weight losses on the same sample at different points can also be used as a diagnosis of the sample's anisotropy.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] For instance, sampling the top side and the bottom side of a sample with dispersed particles inside can be useful to detect sedimentation, as thermograms will not overlap but will show a gap between them if the particle distribution is different from side to side.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Thermogravimetric kinetics may be explored for insight into the reaction mechanisms of thermal (catalytic or non-catalytic) decomposition involved in the pyrolysis and combustion processes of different materials.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Activation energies of the decomposition process can be calculated using Kissinger method.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Though a constant heating rate is more common, a constant mass loss rate can illuminate specific reaction kinetics.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] For example, the kinetic parameters of the carbonization of polyvinyl butyral were found using a constant mass loss rate of 0.2 wt %/min.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] Thermogravimetric analysis is often combined with other processes or used in conjunction with other analytical methods.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] For example, the TGA instrument continuously weighs a sample as it is heated to temperatures of up to 2000 °C for coupling with Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) and mass spectrometry gas analysis.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/thermogravimetric-analysis] As the temperature increases, various components of the sample are decomposed and the weight percentage of each resulting mass change can be measured.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] In chemistry, **volatility** is a material quality which describes how readily a substance vaporizes.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] At a given temperature and pressure, a substance with high volatility is more likely to exist as a vapour, while a substance with low volatility is more likely to be a liquid or solid.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Volatility can also describe the tendency of a vapor to condense into a liquid or solid; less volatile substances will more readily condense from a vapor than highly volatile ones.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Differences in volatility can be observed by comparing how fast substances within a group evaporate (or sublimate in the case of solids) when exposed to the atmosphere.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] A highly volatile substance such as rubbing alcohol (isopropyl alcohol) will quickly evaporate, while a substance with low volatility such as vegetable oil will remain condensed.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] In general, solids are much less volatile than liquids, but there are some exceptions.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Solids that sublimate (change directly from solid to vapor) such as dry ice (solid carbon dioxide) or iodine can vaporize at a similar rate as some liquids under standard conditions.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Volatility itself has no defined numerical value, but it is often described using vapor pressures or boiling points (for liquids).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] High vapor pressures indicate a high volatility, while high boiling points indicate low volatility.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Vapor pressures and boiling points are often presented in tables and charts that can be used to compare chemicals of interest.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Volatility data is typically found through experimentation over a range of temperatures and pressures.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Vapor pressure is a measurement of how readily a condensed phase forms a vapor at a given temperature.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] A substance enclosed in a sealed vessel initially at vacuum (no air inside) will quickly fill any empty space with vapor.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] After the system reaches equilibrium and the rate of evaporation matches the rate of condensation, the vapor pressure can be measured.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Increasing the temperature increases the amount of vapor that is formed and thus the vapor pressure.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] In a mixture, each substance contributes to the overall vapor pressure of the mixture, with more volatile compounds making a larger contribution.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Boiling point is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of a liquid is equal to the surrounding pressure, causing the liquid to rapidly evaporate, or boil.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] It is closely related to vapor pressure, but is dependent on pressure.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The normal boiling point is the boiling point at atmospheric pressure, but it can also be reported at higher and lower pressures.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] An important factor influencing a substance's volatility is the strength of the interactions between its molecules.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Attractive forces between molecules are what holds materials together, and materials with stronger intermolecular forces, such as most solids, are typically not very volatile.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Ethanol and dimethyl ether, two chemicals with the same formula (C2H6O), have different volatilities due to the different interactions that occur between their molecules in the liquid phase: ethanol molecules are capable of hydrogen bonding while dimethyl ether molecules are not.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The result in an overall stronger attractive force between the ethanol molecules, making it the less volatile substance of the two.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] In general, volatility tends to decrease with increasing molecular mass because larger molecules can participate in more intermolecular bonding, although other factors such as structure and polarity play a significant role.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The effect of molecular mass can be partially isolated by comparing chemicals of similar structure (i.e. esters, alkanes, etc.).
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] For instance, linear alkanes exhibit decreasing volatility as the number of carbons in the chain increases.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Knowledge of volatility is often useful in the separation of components from a mixture.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] When a mixture of condensed substances contains multiple substances with different levels of volatility, its temperature and pressure can be manipulated such that the more volatile components change to a vapor while the less volatile substances remain in the liquid or solid phase.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The newly formed vapor can then be discarded or condensed into a separate container.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] When the vapors are collected, this process is known as distillation.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The process of petroleum refinement utilizes a technique known as fractional distillation, which allows several chemicals of varying volatility to be separated in a single step.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Crude oil entering a refinery is composed of many useful chemicals that need to be separated.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The crude oil flows into a distillation tower and is heated up, which allows the more volatile components such as butane and kerosene to vaporize.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] These vapors move up the tower and eventually come in contact with cold surfaces, which causes them to condense and be collected.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The most volatile chemical condense at the top of the column while the least volatile chemicals to vaporize condense in the lowest portion.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The difference in volatility between water and ethanol has long been used to produce concentrated alcoholic beverages (many of these are referred to as "liquors").
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] In order to increase the concentration of ethanol in the product, beverage makers would heat the initial alcohol mixture to a temperature where most of the ethanol vaporizes while most of the water remains liquid.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The ethanol vapor is then collected and condensed in a separate container, resulting in a much more concentrated product.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Volatility is an important consideration when crafting perfumes.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Humans detect odors when aromatic vapors come in contact with receptors in the nose.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Ingredients that vaporize quickly after being applied will produce fragrant vapors for a short time before the oils evaporate.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Slow-evaporating ingredients can stay on the skin for weeks or even months, but may not produce enough vapors to produce a strong aroma.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] To prevent these problems, perfume designers carefully consider the volatility of essential oils and other ingredients in their perfumes.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Appropriate evaporation rates are achieved by modifying the amount of highly volatile and non-volatile ingredients used.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Chemical weapons can be classified as **persistent** **agents** or **nonpersistent agents** dependent on volatility.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] The more volatile an agent, the faster it will evaporate and be dispersed and may only be a danger for a specific period of time.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Persistent agents cause extended contamination and be used for area denial via contamination of the battlefield's choke points or rear.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Volatile and nonpersistent chemical weapons including the early G-series nerve agents, including tabun, sarin, and soman.
[src:thermogravimetric-analysis/volatility-chemistry] Less volatile and more persistent chemical weapons include mustard gas, the V-series nerve agents, including VX and VR, and the Novichok series nerve agents.
